00:42:01.500 --> 00:42:05.999
filling out the forms is no option.
&gt;&gt; ANDERSON: Absolutely.

00:42:05.999 --> 00:42:10.460
&gt;&gt; And, in that being, what do you think about
micro payments versus subscription?

00:42:10.460 --> 00:42:15.100
&gt;&gt; ANDERSON: I'd actually deal with this quite
a bit in the book, the failure of micro payments

00:42:15.100 --> 00:42:20.900
today. There are two barriers, there are two
explanations for the failure of micro payments.

00:42:20.900 --> 00:42:27.029
The first is the one you just said, which
is that the transaction itself is more troubled

00:42:27.029 --> 00:42:33.140
than the revenue opportunity. The second...
And I think overtime that's going to get easier,

00:42:33.140 --> 00:42:37.171
the transaction systems are going to get better.
The second one is psychological. The way to

00:42:37.171 --> 00:42:42.680
think about is this, a price, just think of
any price raises a flag in your head and that

00:42:42.680 --> 00:42:49.570
flag is the sort... Is it worth, that flag?
And you know, that flag is work. We have to

00:42:49.570 --> 00:42:52.990
think, "Do I want this? How much do I want
this? What's the right price for it?" You

00:42:52.990 --> 00:42:56.619
know, "How should I pay? Do I have enough
money? I might want something else?" These

00:42:56.619 --> 00:43:02.780
all fall under the phrase of "mental transaction
costs." Just processing that sort of, should

00:43:02.780 --> 00:43:08.940
I pay, should I not, is work and we are nothing
if not work avoidance machines. So, what Free

00:43:08.940 --> 00:43:14.010
allows you to do is it allows you to thoughtlessly
consume. You don't have to go to that thought

00:43:14.010 --> 00:43:19.640
process. Now, this is what the venture capitalist
Josh Kopelman calls the Penny gap. The difference

00:43:19.640 --> 00:43:26.330
in one penny and zero cents is economically
insignificant but psychologically black and

00:43:26.330 --> 00:43:31.619
white, night and day. And the problem with
Micropayments is that they all have the psychological

00:43:31.619 --> 00:43:37.390
downsides of a price without any of the revenue
upsides of a real price. So, what's happened

00:43:37.390 --> 00:43:42.410
now? When you hear now—when people talk
about Micropayments and you actually look

00:43:42.410 --> 00:43:46.619
at what they're talking about, they're talking
about 99 cents, $1.99. Micropayments used

00:43:46.619 --> 00:43:52.369
to be fractional cents. And now they're a
buck, 2 bucks, 3 bucks those are just transactions.

00:43:52.369 --> 00:43:57.140
And at that point, when the transactions engines
become so efficient, be it, you know, the

00:43:57.140 --> 00:44:02.570
iPhone, iTune store or the emerging, you know,
the emerging sort of transaction system within

00:44:02.570 --> 00:44:12.080
Facebook, within iPod Apps, iPhone Apps, PayPal,
what you guys are going to do with Android

00:44:12.080 --> 00:44:17.410
as well. That side of the barrier at entry
declines. Is that it's you don't have to pull

00:44:17.410 --> 00:44:20.609
out your credit card, you don't have to type
in your details, it's just a thoughtless click.

00:44:20.609 --> 00:44:27.700
The question is, those psychological cost
remain, how far can the price go? How far

00:44:27.700 --> 00:44:35.020
down can that price go where it can still—-the
revenue upside compensates for the psychology

00:44:35.020 --> 00:44:42.140
downside of a real price? Is it 99 cents,
is it 79 cents, is it 29 cents? You know,

00:44:42.140 --> 00:44:47.760
we don't know. But it's now almost entirely
or will be going forward almost entirely about

00:44:47.760 --> 00:44:54.570
psychology, the consumer psychology of price,
rather than that structural problem of the

00:44:54.570 --> 00:45:02.359
transaction hassles itself. Yes?
&gt;&gt; Yes. I wanted to ask you, what are your

00:45:02.359 --> 00:45:06.960
thoughts on Radiohead's experimental awhile
back "Within Rainbow's" where they asked consumers

00:45:06.960 --> 00:45:11.460
to name their own price, most people ended
up paying nothing for it. Would have they

00:45:11.460 --> 00:45:15.500
been better off just saying, "Here's the free
and we'll make our money off concerts and

00:45:15.500 --> 00:45:18.240
off premium CDs and everything like that."
&gt;&gt; ANDERSON: Yes, that's a great question.

00:45:18.240 --> 00:45:26.240
So, what Radiohead did is a classic product
segmentation strategy. So, in the old days

00:45:26.240 --> 00:45:31.519
of music you pretty much had three prices.
There was the album, the single, and the tour.

00:45:31.519 --> 00:45:38.549
So, it was like, 15 bucks, 5 bucks, and $85,
okay. So, what Radiohead did, is they basically

00:45:38.549 --> 00:45:44.640
introduced not three skews or 15 skews, but
something like 35 skews; different forms of

00:45:44.640 --> 00:45:49.160
the album. So, there was--actually those were
just the products. There were the individual

00:45:49.160 --> 00:45:52.020
tracks; they were tracks of different bit
rates; there was the vinyl; there was the

00:45:52.020 --> 00:45:57.569
CD; there was the box set; there was the box;
there was the book; there was the video; there

00:45:57.569 --> 00:46:03.480
was the concert tour; there were the T-shirts.
You know, it went on, I'm sure there were

00:46:03.480 --> 00:46:08.400
the action figures—-I didn't see it, I wouldn't
be surprised. So, what they did is rather

00:46:08.400 --> 00:46:13.920
than having three prices they had, you know,
they had at least 30 for the skews then you

00:46:13.920 --> 00:46:18.450
can name your own price. So, they had an infinite
continuum of prices ranging from zero all

00:46:18.450 --> 00:46:24.170
the way to front row seats in Wembley Stadium
that's, you know, at $500. What that allows

00:46:24.170 --> 00:46:29.740
you to do is it allows you to maximize the
economic value in the market place. By letting

00:46:29.740 --> 00:46:34.460
people choose their own price, they were able
to, you know, to get the people who-—not

00:46:34.460 --> 00:46:38.900
only the people who want to pay less but also
the people who are willing to pay more. By

00:46:38.900 --> 00:46:42.821
having this difference--by saying, "Well,
it's not that you get the album, the single

00:46:42.821 --> 00:46:47.770
or the tour but also for our super fans, there's
the $100 box set," they're able to tap that

00:46:47.770 --> 00:46:51.650
side of the market as well. And by using Free,
as one of the options, they're able to, not

00:46:51.650 --> 00:46:56.890
only maximize the reach and let everyone sample
the album, but they also got lot of attention

00:46:56.890 --> 00:46:59.690
for the experiment in the first place. The
result was, they had the most successful tour

00:46:59.690 --> 00:47:04.490
in their history, they had the most box set
sold-don't hold me on this number, I maybe

00:47:04.490 --> 00:47:08.940
making it up-I think they sold a hundred thousand
of the box sets at the very high price. It

00:47:08.940 --> 00:47:12.910
was one of the, I think, one of the most successful
albums, if not, the most successful album.

00:47:12.910 --> 00:47:20.630
It was a total economic win along all lines
and they did it by being clever about offering

00:47:20.630 --> 00:47:25.220
lots of premiums to go with there free. They
segmented their products into lots of different

00:47:25.220 --> 00:47:32.009
price categories and lots of different audience
categories ranging from not very engage—-I've

00:47:32.009 --> 00:47:35.270
never heard Radiohead just want to sample
one—-all the way to, "Oh my God. I love

00:47:35.270 --> 00:47:40.720
Radiohead. I want everything they do and more."
And that, I think, is what all of us have

00:47:40.720 --> 00:47:45.240
to do, I think, we in the media industry,
we need to figure out, we know... I'm a magazine

00:47:45.240 --> 00:47:51.640
editor. We have Zero, that's our website,
$5 that's our newsstand price and 80 cents.

00:47:51.640 --> 00:47:59.970
That's $10 a year divided by 12 issues, 80ish.
That's not enough. Where's our 29.95? Where's

00:47:59.970 --> 00:48:05.680
our 39.95? Where's our 99.95? Where's our
Radiohead? Where's our pet for our penguin?

00:48:05.680 --> 00:48:10.330
You know, how are we going to find ways? We
use Free, we use Free successfully. Now, we

00:48:10.330 --> 00:48:15.309
need to figure out how to use free to charge
more. How to segment our audience into—-not

00:48:15.309 --> 00:48:18.730
just hose who came in at those three prices,
but those who, maybe if we could have packaged

00:48:18.730 --> 00:48:23.190
what we do in different ways including the
physical experience, we could charge a lot

00:48:23.190 --> 00:48:27.150
more. If you followed recently the scandal
over the Washington Post charging $25,000

00:48:27.150 --> 00:48:35.009
to have lunch--dinner with the editors, that
was their effort to find a pet for your penguin.

00:48:35.009 --> 00:48:41.910
Yes.
&gt;&gt; Do you think that Free has changed the

00:48:41.910 --> 00:48:47.119
users' or the consumers' concept of quality?
&gt;&gt; ANDERSON: Yes, that's a great question.

00:48:47.119 --> 00:48:49.839
It is also addressed somewhat in the book.
But there's—-you know, you get what you

00:48:49.839 --> 00:48:54.700
pay for, right, there's this conception. Interestingly,
there's another author named, Ellen Ruppel

00:48:54.700 --> 00:48:58.279
Shell, who came out with a book at the same
time called "Cheap: The High Price of Discount

00:48:58.279 --> 00:49:04.609
Culture." But there's a general... So, it's
all based on your starting position. I tell

00:49:04.609 --> 00:49:09.190
the story of the "Village Voice" which is
a weekly newspaper in New York that went free

00:49:09.190 --> 00:49:14.119
and everyone said... You know, when they went
free their quality declined. You know, that

00:49:14.119 --> 00:49:19.240
you get what you paid for and that the free
reflected the underlying values. Not actually

00:49:19.240 --> 00:49:23.119
true, I would argue, but that's what people
thought. But no one thinks that Google is

00:49:23.119 --> 00:49:27.559
a worst search engine because it's free and
that's because our expectation, our correlation

00:49:27.559 --> 00:49:34.440
between price and quality was never set above
zero, and it's all based on that. If a product

00:49:34.440 --> 00:49:39.060
starts at zero, you don't use price as a test
of quality. If a product starts at a price

00:49:39.060 --> 00:49:43.819
and goes to zero, you might think that it
was worth less. Now, there are exemptions

00:49:43.819 --> 00:49:49.549
to the rule, Yahoomail, I told the story of
Yahoomail versus Gmail in the book. Yahoomail

00:49:49.549 --> 00:49:53.119
was 5 megabytes for free and anything more
you have to pay for it—-I think it was 29.95

00:49:53.119 --> 00:49:57.799
a year—-they--with the release of Gmail,
they [INDISTINCT] that business. They basically

00:49:57.799 --> 00:50:04.789
went to infinite storage for free, forever.
Because Gmail had entered the market at, I

00:50:04.789 --> 00:50:10.930
think, a gigabyte for free, people didn't
think that Yahoomail had declined in quality

00:50:10.930 --> 00:50:15.620
as a result. In other words, Gmail reset the
consumer correlation between price and quality.

00:50:15.620 --> 00:50:19.849
I think in the digital space, in the physical
space, I think we have a very clean connection

00:50:19.849 --> 00:50:24.920
between price and quality. And if it says,
you know, if it says—-if something is free

00:50:24.920 --> 00:50:29.099
and, you know, pair of socks is free, you
probably should expect they're not the best

00:50:29.099 --> 00:50:33.990
socks in the world. In the digital space,
I don't think we make that same correlation

00:50:33.990 --> 00:50:38.059
because we understand that the subsidies can
be so defuse and the underline cost are so

00:50:38.059 --> 00:50:42.109
low that we don't assume that only crap is
free.

